## VOICE/TONE RECOMMENDATION

### Recommended Voice
Refined Design Analyst

### Tone Characteristics
- Precision over enthusiasm (describe chromatic relationships, not "super cute combos")
- Instructional minimalism (direct guidance, zero hand-holding language)
- Technical fluency with restraint (use color theory terms naturally but don't lecture)
- Gallery-style rhythm (short declarative sentences, visual breathing room)
- Elevated vernacular ("study in asymmetry" not "fun mismatched vibes")

### Language Style
- Zero exclamation points (period always)
- Active voice, minimal adjectives ("Consider" not "You might want to consider")
- Avoid questions to reader ("What colors work?" → "Analogous colors create harmony")
- No validation-seeking ("trust us," "believe me")
- Sensory language for finishes (luminous, diffused, reflective vs "shiny," "pretty")
- Technical precision (opacity, chromatic shift, tonal consistency)

### Audience Match
Voice suits the creative but style-conscious audience seeking permission to break symmetry rules *with intention*. Speaks to readers who want sophisticated asymmetry, not juvenile randomness. Matches cluster requirement for refined tastemaker positioning—treats nail art as design discipline, not craft project.

